pr_title: Fix reading metadata from ELF sections
pr_body:
This PR fixes reading in the ELF sections related to metadata. Since the Section Table Header and String Table are not present in the process, we read them from the executable's file instead. We then read the relevant sections from the offset given by the Section Table Header in the process's address space.

@adrian-prantl @vedantk

pr_title: Add functionality that returns correct reflection section name for different object files (Mach-O, ELF, COFF)
pr_body:
This is used by https://github.com/apple/llvm-project/pull/1608 in order to get the correct reflection section name.

@adrian-prantl @vedantk

pr_title: Fix reading elf section from file buffer
pr_body:
This pr fixes a bug where reading elf sections from the file buffer would read less data than intended.

@adrian-prantl

pr_title: Use new libReflection API when reading ELF files
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 466541559, 'comment_body': "We shouldn't make this a compile-time decision. You could be debugging a Linux binary from a macOS machine. That's actually a very common scenario for server development on macOS.
Ideally these strings should live in a single location in a header file in the Swift compiler.

I would suggest a Swift compiler patch that adds a new file 

`include/swift/ABI/ObjectFile.h`

where you define a base class with one Mach-O and one ELF implementation that has a `getFieldMD()` or a `getSectionName(enum SectionType)` method or something similar.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 6, 16, 38, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrian-prantl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 466541878, 'comment_body': 'And then use that in `ReflectionContext.h` so the strings only live in a single place.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 6, 16, 39, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrian-prantl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 466543537, 'comment_body': 'Can you leave a comment here explaining why ELF needs special treatment?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 6, 16, 41, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrian-prantl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 466543876, 'comment_body': 'ðŸ¤©', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 6, 16, 42, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrian-prantl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 466579283, 'comment_body': "Ok! pr_body:
This PR enables tests that were passing on Linux but are currently skipped.

@adrian-prantl @vedantk

pr_title: Enables tests passing after fix of parsing elf object files
Adds entry points to the runtime that exposes metadata
pr_body: This PR will add the necessary functionality in order to enable SwiftReflectionTest to work on Linux. This will be done by adding entry points in the Swift runtime that only build in debug builds

The old algorithm would mistakenly assume that the sections would go from address 0x7f22a7334244 up to 0x7f22a734927c, which is 15038 bytes long.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 20, 7, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'augusto2112', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455320691, 'comment_body': "@jckarter I just remembered why they aren't conditionalized here. The problem is that `SwiftReflectionTest.swift` is built even when assertions are off. To conditionalize them here, I'd have to change the CMake config to only build this file in debug or on Mac. I initally did that, but was asked to roll-back that change. These functions are conditionalized in C++ though, so I believe calling them would crash the program, which isn't ideal. 
In order to conditionalize these symbols, in `SwiftReflectionTest.swift`, when on Linux but not in debug, stub the required functions so it as least compiles. Is this solution ok?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 20, 25, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'augusto2112', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455360630, 'comment_body': "'reflection_test_support' sounds better than 'basic_reflection_support' to me, since it's not clear what the basic/non-basic distinction is.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 21, 24, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vedantk', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455465869, 'comment_body': 'They are sections only on ELF because of the restrictions from the file format.  Each one of those is a separate metadata table.  In fact, if you look at MachO, they are all in the `__DATA` section and each is a segment.  PE/COFF does something similar - entries are grouped, and then emitted entirely into the `.data` section.  If this is meant to be ELF specific, please put that into the name (e.g. `swift_remote_reflection_elf_section`).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 2, 3, 34, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'compnerd', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455466748, 'comment_body': "Like the previous comment, I don't think that the term section should play into this.  I would say that it represents a (contiguous) region in the image's address space.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 2, 6, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'compnerd', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455467399, 'comment_body': "Yeah, I don't think that it really is correct to encode the details of a specific file format into the name.  The nomenclature in the `ReflectionInfo` stems from it being specific to ELF.  If we want this to be limited to ELF, I think that we should be putting ELF into the name of the types (assuming that we will want custom types for MachO, WASM, COFF).  I think that the types here are pretty generic though.  I think that something like `swift_reflection_address_mapping` works well as this maps the local address to the remote address.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 2, 9, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'compnerd', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455468742, 'comment_body': "I think that the clarification that was made further up is _critical_ here.  It isn't that the reflection info is non-contiguous.  The metadata layout _is_ contiguous.  The mapping from local to remote is non-contiguous.  Is that understanding incorrect?  If not, this is misleading, and I would say that this is better named as perhaps `swift_remote_reflection_data_slice` to indicate that this is a sliver of the full metadata information.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 2, 14, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'compnerd', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456000709, 'comment_body': 'Sorry, by "subsection" I mean one of the individual areas referenced in the `reflection_info` struct, like `field`, `associated_types`, and so on. Anyway, the `swift_reflection_info` and `swift_reflection_addReflectionInfo` interfaces are obsolete, and I'm saying it would be good to name these new ones `swift_reflection_addReflectionInfo2` or something like that to make it clear it should supersede the old interface.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 18, 50, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jckarter', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456001376, 'comment_body': "You have that backwards, `__DATA` is the segment (they're actually in `__TEXT`, though, because they're constant), and `__TEXT, __swift5_foo` is the section, in Mach-O parlance. The name seems correct to me.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 18, 52, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jckarter', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456002529, 'comment_body': 'What was wrong with conditionalizing SwiftReflectionTest.swift? If touching CMake is inappropriate, maybe we could #if out the contents.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 18, 53, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jckarter', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456164387, 'comment_body': 'Ah, okay, if that is constant across all the formats, sounds reasonable.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 17, 1, 16, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'compnerd', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Unify COFF and ELF data structures and procedures
pr_body:
This PR unifies the `MetadataSections` data structure present both in `ImageInspectionELF.h` and `ImageInspectionCOFF.h`, as well as prepare it to be accessible from Swift. It also unifies the procedures which were identical under ELF and COFF in a new `ImageInspectionCommon` file.

@vedantk @compnerd

This PR moves the `MetadataSections` definition from ImageInspectionELF to SwiftShims. This is part of the work in unifying the definition of `MetadataSections`, in order to be used by both ELF and COFF-specific procedures, as well as being acessible from Swift for testing purposes.

pr_title: Enable validation reflection tests passing on Linux
pr_body:
This PR enables the tests validation tests (with the new `reflection_test_support` directive) that are already passing on Linux with no further modifications necessary after the work done in #32339.

@vedantk @adrian-prantl

Quoting @tbkka: `The number of extra inhabitants actually depends to some extent on the OS. Apple platforms reserve a 4GB "page zero" on 64 bit platforms in order to help detect 32/64 bit errors. [...] But Linux only reserves a 4K page zero, so there are only 4096 invalid pointer values.`

This PR adds variables `num_extra_inhabitants`, `num_extra_inhabitants_minus_1`, `num_extra_inhabitants_minus_2` and `num_extra_inhabitants_minus_3`, with the proper platform's values, and replaces the usages of those raw values by the variables.

It also enables the tests under Linux which are now working thanks to these changes and #32339.
pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 461162348, 'comment_body': 'It\'s possible to specify numeric variables in FileCheck now using "-D#foo=val", see https://llvm.org/docs/CommandGuide/FileCheck.html#filecheck-numeric-substitution-blocks. I think that would be a good fit here, since it\'d allow us to just introduce one predefined value. For example we could write "-D#num_extra_inhabitants_64bit=4096" in lit.cfg, then write "[[#num_extra_inhabitants_64bit]]", "[[#num_extra_inhabitants_64bit-1]]", etc. in tests.\r\n', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 27, 20, 51, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vedantk', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 461187928, 'comment_body': 'It looks way cleaner now! Just waiting for the current tests to end before pushing.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 27, 21, 43, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'augusto2112', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Disable loading scalars as addresses when materializing an entity variable
pr_body:
This PR disables the incorrect loading of scalars as addresses in the context of the entity variable's materializer, which caused problems when materializing a variable from a register. This also enables a test which was affected by this bug on Linux.

@adrian-prantl @vedantk although this bug manifested on Linux, I believe it could affect other platforms as well, right? Also, the failing test happened to catch this behavior, but it wasn't really its intended purpose. Do you think it'd be worthwhile to craft a new test to check this behavior specifically?

        """Test that the generic self in a protocol extension works in the expression evaluator.
        """
        self.build()

        lldbutil.run_to_source_breakpoint(self, "break here",
                                          lldb.SBFileSpec('main.swift'))
        self.expect("e f", substrs=[' = 12345'])
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 14, 19, 49, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrian-prantl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 454603952, 'comment_body': 'and replace this comment with `// break here`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 14, 19, 50, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adrian-prantl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 454604389, 'comment_body': 'I know that this is about self in a register, but the way the test is written we really have no control over that.
